Germany, Year Zero
May 8th always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide as after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
After the Nazis left, the occupying powers had not yet established an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry I recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies indulged in every excess.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was transported directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and was tasked with setting up - from nothing - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, although for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But what for?
What future?
“You must help,” my mother said.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special "victim of fascism" card, while others displayed a Iron Cross awarded for late services to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, and almost everyone mourned the loss of loved ones.
Yet this phase did not last.
It is almost unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and especially accompanied by a new form of servitude.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and detainees.
In contrast, after a short period of unfriendliness, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled enhancement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not just an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Admittedly, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and everyone wanted to consolidate “their” part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic nature, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy unquestionably takes root more easily in a context of economic revival.
This requires, above all, initiative from individuals who wish to end a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the “social market economy” in Germany), but things are easier with a starting capital.
Hence the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
The European Union also helped the former communist countries, and continues to support them in their efforts.
The other moral lesson is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of the Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not begin its long journey by focusing on the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of “restoration,” because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their positions.
In a way, the country ignored its past in order to move forward toward the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced its past, with great success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other traumatized countries therefore tend to confuse.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to confront the past.
In the end, it is a better approach.
In Europe, May 8th 2005 is an occasion to look back at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
